Kubernetes Components
CONTROL PLANE (Master Node / Brain)
The control plane makes decisions and manages the cluster state.
It does not run application containers.
1ï¸âƒ£ API Server
Definition
The API Server is the central entry point of the Kubernetes cluster that handles all requests and communication.
Explanation
All commands (kubectl, CI/CD, UI, controllers) go through API Server
Validates requests
Updates or reads cluster state from etcd
Acts as a hub between all components

ğŸ“Œ Key Point
If API Server is down â†’ cluster is unusable

2ï¸âƒ£ Scheduler
Definition
The Scheduler decides which worker node a Pod should run on.
Explanation
Watches for newly created Pods with no assigned node
Evaluates:
CPU & memory availability
Node health
Constraints & policies
Assigns Pod to the best node
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
Scheduler does placement, not execution

3ï¸âƒ£ Controller Manager
Definition
The Controller Manager ensures the desired state matches the actual state of the cluster.
Explanation
Continuously monitors cluster
If something breaks â†’ fixes it automatically
Examples:
Pod dies â†’ new Pod created
Node fails â†’ Pods rescheduled
Replicas < desired â†’ create more
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
This is where self-healing comes from

4ï¸âƒ£ etcd
Definition
etcd is a distributed key-value database that stores the entire cluster state.
Explanation
Stores:
Nodes
Pods
Secrets
ConfigMaps
Desired state
Highly consistent & reliable
Single source of truth
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
If etcd data is lost â†’ cluster state is lost

WORKER NODE (Execution Layer)
Worker nodes run application workloads.
5ï¸âƒ£ kubelet
Definition
The kubelet is a node-level agent that executes instructions from the control plane.
Explanation
Communicates with API Server
Ensures containers described in Pod spec are running
Monitors Pod & container health
Reports node status back to control plane
âœ” Acts as:
Agent
Executor of the brain
Caretaker of the node
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
kubelet does NOT decide â€” it executes

6ï¸âƒ£ kube-proxy (Service Proxy)
Definition
kube-proxy manages network communication and basic load balancing for Services.
Explanation
Runs on every worker node
Handles:
Pod-to-Pod communication
Service-to-Pod routing
Uses iptables / IPVS
Provides stable access to Pods
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
kube-proxy enables service-level load balancing, not application LB

7ï¸âƒ£ Container Runtime
Definition
The container runtime is the software that actually runs containers.
Explanation
Examples:
Docker
containerd
CRI-O
Pulls images
Creates containers
Starts and stops containers
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
Kubernetes does not run containers itself
It instructs the container runtime


CLIENT TOOL (NOT PART OF NODE)

8ï¸âƒ£ kubectl (Corrected)
Definition
kubectl is a command-line client tool used to interact with the Kubernetes cluster.
Explanation
Sends requests to API Server
Can be run from:
Laptop
CI/CD server
Bastion host
âŒ Not part of master or worker
âœ” Only communicates through API Server
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
kubectl = CLI interface, NOT a cluster component

NETWORKING
9ï¸âƒ£ CNI (Container Network Interface)
Definition
CNI is a networking plugin framework that provides network connectivity to Pods.
Explanation
Ensures:
Every Pod gets a unique IP
Pod-to-Pod communication across nodes
Examples:
Calico
Flannel
Weave
Installed by default in managed clusters (EKS, GKE, AKS)
ğŸ“Œ Key Point
Without CNI â†’ Pods cannot communicate



